1. Reaffirms the importance of the independence of public service broadcasting organisations as an essential factor of pluralistic communication;
2. Recalls the commitments accepted by the representatives of the states participating in the 4th European Ministerial Conference on Mass Media Policy (Prague, 7-8 December 1994) in the framework of Resolution No. 1 on the future of public service broadcasting, especially respect for the independence of public service broadcasting organisations;
3. Notes the need to develop further the principles on the independence of public service broadcasting set out in the aforementioned Prague resolution in the light of the challenges raised by political, economic and technological change in 1990s and the increasing importance of the role of public service broadcasting in the information society;
